Headlines.Author: Chana R. Schoenberger

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Monday.) NEW YORK -(Dow Jones)- China has made it easier for overseas companies to buy from local suppliers and pay their Chinese employees in yuan. But they've found few takers among U.S. firms. American companies have poured into China to take advantage of low labor costs and a burgeoning consumer market. The weak yuan lowers the cost of manufacturing in China, making goods produced there more competitive when selling abroad. But over the last year that advantage has been eroded by rising inflation in China, and Beijing's decision to raise the range it allows the yuan to trade against the dollar.

But they've found few takers among U.S. firms. American companies have poured into China to take advantage of low labor costs and a burgeoning consumer market. The weak yuan lowers the cost of manufacturing in China, making goods produced there more competitive when selling abroad. But over the last year that advantage has been eroded by rising inflation in China, and Beijing's decision to raise the range it allows the yuan to trade against the dollar.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: US Firms Slow To Embrace Yuan

#text: Harman International Industries Inc.'s

fiscal second-quarter net income fell 47% on higher expenses as the company announced plant closings resulting in 500 job cuts. PARAGRAPH.#text:
Stock funds collected nearly $13 billion in new investments in March, far above
    February's figure of $712 million, but still well below figures from a year earlier the
    Investment Company Institute reported Thursday. For the entire first quarter cash flow
    into funds was $31 billion, down almost 50 percent from the first quarter of 1998 when it
    was $61 billion.
